Raw dev notes -- Landing Page Updates & Cloudflare Woes

Okay, so this batch of work was mostly focused on the landing page for my Hebrew RTL browser extension. For context, the extension helps fix right-to-left text issues on websites, especially for Hebrew, making the browsing experience much smoother for users. The landing page is where people discover it, learn about its features, and get the link to install it.

This past week or so, a few things landed. The biggest chunk was probably around the privacy policy. Ugh, legal stuff. I had to add a dedicated privacy policy page, which is a requirement for the Chrome Web Store. It wasn't just a copy-paste job; I spent a good chunk of time restyling it to match the existing landing page theme, which was a nice touch but still felt like a chore. The real brain-bender was adding specific details about Israeli privacy law and data rights, and clarifying *exactly* what data the extension stores (spoiler: just booleans for hostnames, nothing personally identifiable). It's always a struggle to translate legal jargon into something understandable while still being accurate.

Then there was the whole saga of the automated selector health check. The extension relies on specific CSS selectors to identify and fix RTL issues on various sites. My brilliant idea was to set up a GitHub Action to regularly visit a list of sites and check if those selectors were still valid. I got it working, fixed some initial kinks like handling Cloudflare (or so I thought), adding issue creation if a selector broke, and bumping Node to 22. It felt like a really smart, proactive way to maintain the extension.

But, alas, the web had other plans. Almost immediately after getting the automated check running, it started failing consistently. Turns out, most of the sites I wanted to check were behind Cloudflare or required a login, which completely blocked my automated script. It was a classic case of "great idea, but reality bites." After a couple of days of trying to tweak it, I had to disable the scheduled check entirely. It was a bit deflating, honestly, to put that effort in only for it to be rendered useless by real-world web defenses.

On the brighter side, I also got to add some new feature cards to the landing page. The extension itself has been getting some cool updates, like "Deep Research RTL" and "Claude Artifacts" integration (which is super neat for complex text analysis), plus better keyboard control and smart input RTL. It's always satisfying to update the marketing material to reflect actual product improvements. Bumped the landing page version a couple of times too, to 2.2.1 and then 2.2.3.

Reflecting on it, the privacy policy work felt like a necessary evil. It's important to be transparent and compliant, but it's definitely not the fun part of development. The selector check failure was a good, albeit frustrating, lesson in the limitations of web automation. Sometimes, you just can't fight the big guns like Cloudflare, and you have to accept that a manual approach (or relying on user reports) is the more practical path. It felt like a small defeat, but also a realistic one. It's a reminder that not every clever solution works out in the wild. Still, seeing the new features go live on the page felt like a win, showcasing the actual value being added.

Next up: Probably more extension features, then more landing page updates.
